Ratio data is the highest level of measurement scale. It has the following characteristics:

* It can be ordered or ranked.
* The differences between values are meaningful.
* There is a true zero.

The strong point of ratio data is that it allows for the greatest amount of mathematical manipulation. Ratio data can be added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided. This makes it possible to perform a wide variety of statistical analyses on ratio data.

For example, we can calculate the mean, median, mode, range, and standard deviation of ratio data. We can also use ratio data to test hypotheses and make predictions.

Ratio data is often used in scientific and engineering applications. It is also used in business and finance. For example, businesses use ratio data to track sales, costs, and profits. Financial institutions use ratio data to assess the creditworthiness of borrowers.

Overall, ratio data is a valuable tool for understanding and analyzing data. It is the highest level of measurement scale and allows for the greatest amount of mathematical manipulation. This makes it possible to perform a wide variety of statistical analyses on ratio data.
